---
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
	title="Security"
	description="Security principles in OrgOps: least privilege, auditable actions, explicit side effects, and safe secret handling."
>
	<header class="hero">
		<h1>Security</h1>
		<p class="lede">
			OrgOps is built around the idea that automation should be inspectable and controllable. Security is a product
			feature, not an afterthought.
		</p>
	</header>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Principles</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Least privilege:</strong> scope secrets and capabilities to what’s needed.</li>
			<li><strong>Auditability:</strong> actions are represented as events you can review.</li>
			<li><strong>Explicit side effects:</strong> prefer command envelopes over hidden network calls.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Secrets</h2>
		<p>
			Secrets are stored encrypted and injected as environment variables when needed. Agents can set/list/delete keys, but do not read secret values back.
		</p>
		<p>
			This keeps workflows automatable without turning the event log into a credential leak.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<h2>Operational hygiene</h2>
		<p>
			A few defaults that keep automation safe and debuggable:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Avoid printing environment variables or tokens into logs.</li>
			<li>Rotate keys if exposure is suspected.</li>
			<li>Prefer redaction/tombstoning over hard deletes for audit trails.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
	.hero {
		padding: 1.5rem 0 1rem;
	}
	.lede {
		max-width: 70ch;
		color: rgb(var(--muted));
	}
	.section {
		margin-top: 2.25rem;
		max-width: 75ch;
	}
</style>
